 inspired by the work of Peter Green, document the interaction between life and the arts that has made art more lively and life more artful in sixteen essays with subjects ranging from antiquity to modern times.With topics ranging from Antigone to D. H. Lawrence and Norman Douglas, and from Bactrian coins to Livy's characterization of women, the scope, the zest, and the scholarship of these essays will illuminate new avenues in our understanding of the relationship between classics and culture, and in our appreciation of both the artistic products that have come down to us and the varieties of life from which they spring.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCivilization, WesternxClassical influences. 4aGreek and Roman. 4aantiquity. 4aclassical antiquity. 4aclassical archaeology. 4aclassical. 4ahistory of art. 4ahistory. 4athe arts. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aBadian, Ernst, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoegehold, Alan L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorza, Eugene N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurstein, Stanley M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelia, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisner, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngels, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrost, Frank J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalinsky, Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruen, Erich S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolt, Frank L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoorton, Rich